A black box in your car?
While U.S. road network planners are struggling to find the money needed to repair decaying highway infrastructure, many are seeing a solution in the form of a small black box that sits above your car’s dashboard.
The devices, which record all the miles driven by a motorist and transmit the information to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt in Washington and in government offices to overhaul the outdated system of financing major American roads.
The generally uninteresting sector of major axes planning has suddenly provoked a lively debate and turbulent alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups to pressure the government to use the small boxes to keep track of the miles you travel, and possibly the road you travel, and then use the information to draft a tax bill.
The Tea Party is terrified.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses its concern regarding the protection of privacy.
And while members of Congress can’t agree on whether to continue, several states haven’t waited.
They are looking at how, over the next decade, they will be able to switch to a system that allows drivers to pay based on the number of miles traveled.
Thousands of motorists have already boarded these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS monitoring system, for an experimental ride.
This is truly essential for our nation.
“It’s not like we have a choice,” said Hasan Ikhrata, general manager of the Southern California Association of Governments, which predicts the state will begin recording the miles traveled by every Californian driver by 2025.
There will be a change in the way we pay these taxes.
Technology is here to do that.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country’s Highway Trust Fund, funded with taxes that Americans pay at the pump, is financially dry.
Americans don't buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars can travel more miles with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax, even by 1 cent, while gasoline prices are high.
“The gas tax is simply not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently had trackers installed on 500 cars to test a mile payment system.
“This turns out to be the most logical alternative in the long run,” he said.
Wonks calls this a mileage charge.
It is not surprising that the idea appeals to urban liberals, since taxes could be used to change driving habits so as to reduce congestion and gas emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to achieve the goals set out in the state’s ambitious global warming laws.
But Rep. Bill Shuster (R-Pa.), chairman of the Transportation Committee of the House of Representatives, said he also considered it the most viable alternative in the long term.
Proponents of the Reason Foundation’s free market also appreciate the idea of charging drivers per mile.
“It’s not just a tax going into a big black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits they get.
The move is also supported by two former U.S. transportation secretaries who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to go down the road of payment per mile.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have involved about 10,000 cars.
But the House presidency killed the proposal, addressing the concerns of rural lawmakers representing voters who have to travel many miles every day to get to their work or city.
Several states and major cities, however, are making progress on their side.
The most determined is Oregon, which has mobilized 5,000 drivers to conduct the most important experience in the country.
These drivers will soon pay the state mileage fees instead of gasoline taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is considering one.
Illinois is attempting a trial on a limited number of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transport in states along the U.S. East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida) is studying how it could implement the change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer drivers recently equipped their cars with an aircraft, drivers were concerned that the government could follow their slightest deeds and gestures.
“The concerns about Big Brother and things like that are a big deal,” said Alauddin Khan, who heads strategic performance management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It's not something people want.
At the start of the test, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its site: "It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into full-fledged location devices."
It is not necessary to build a huge and cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people’s daily comings and goings.
Nevada is one of the few states that are now struggling to find affordable technology that would allow the state to know how many miles a car travels, but without knowing the exact place or time.
If we can do that, Khan added, citizens will be more comfortable.
The research of this technology has led some state agencies to call on a small start-up in California called True Mileage.
Originally, the company was not intended to help motorists who pay taxes to states.
It was looking to break into the emerging auto insurance market, where drivers would pay based on their mileage.
But the devices she tests have appealed to the planners of the major axes because they do not use GPS and provide a limited amount of information, periodically downloaded by modem.
“People will be more inclined to do this if you don’t record their speed and locate them,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
Major errors have been made in the pilot programmes of some States.
There are far less expensive ways and far less intrusive methods of doing so.
In Oregon, planners try the experiment by offering drivers different choices.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They may still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a package based on the average number of miles traveled by all state residents.
Other states hope to sell the concept to suspicious citizens by allowing devices to do more, rather than not enough.
In New York City, transportation officials are looking to develop a taxation device that would also be equipped to pay for parking fees, provide “pay-to-drive” insurance, and create a set of real-time speed data from other drivers that drivers could use to avoid traffic jams.
“Automobilists would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits that the system offers them,” said an urban planning document.
However, some transport planners wonder if the whole mileage debate isn't just a huge diversion.
At the San Francisco Bay Area Metropolitan Transportation Commission, officials say Congress could very simply manage the bankruptcy of the Highway Trust Fund by raising taxes on gasoline.
A single or additional annual tax could be imposed on drivers of hybrid vehicles and others whose vehicles do not consume a lot of gasoline, so that everyone pays their fair share.
“There is no need for radical surgery when you simply need aspirin,” said Randy Rentschler, the commission’s director of legislation and public affairs.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists will worry about protecting their privacy and a lot of other things.
David Bowie: Four Unreleased Albums
The English musician has not finished surprising this year.
Starting from The Next Day, which was released in January, he has concocted a luxury reissue scheduled for November 4, with several unreleased.
Four have already emerged on the Web.
The announcement of the release of a new album by David Bowie had left everyone pantyhose.
On his 66th birthday, January 8, 2013, he announced that a new album would be released in March.
After ten years of silence (the last record, Reality, from 2003) and too few appearances in public, the English musician proved that he could still be counted on to sparkle the pop scene.
A feast for his fans
Not tired of surprises, David Bowie had more than one ride in his bag with The Next Day.
Thin White Duke is releasing the album on November 4.
For the occasion, he concocted a real feast for his fans.
This reissue, titled The Next Day Extra, will come in the form of three discs: the original album, previously unreleased studio sessions and remixes, as well as a DVD containing the four previously unveiled clips.
The Next Day Extra will contain a total of ten additional tracks from the original album: the three tracks from the Deluxe Edition, five songs specially unveiled for the occasion, as well as two remixes.
David Bowie made the presentations of this beautiful box in a video.
He introduces both each of the discs, but also the accessories provided with: exclusive photos and covers, a notebook to share his own impressions, a booklet with the lyrics...
And, above all, it gives a taste of his new title Atomica, typically in the vein of The Next Day, with guitars far ahead and a rock electricity cleverly mastered.
Unreleased already listening
But Atomica is not the only title to reveal its charms.
The Informer, Like A Rocket Man, Born In A UFO are also available on the web.
The Informer is double-sided: a disturbing intro before a luminous ride that gradually slows down to make way for a pop ballad.
On Like A Rocket Man, did Bowie want to make a small reference to Elton John’s Rocket Man, or even to Gravity?
With this playful title, the singer seems at least in his element when he no longer has his feet on the ground.
Space Oddity, next door, was much more serious.
On Born In A UFO, David Bowie once again makes reference to his strangeness: Would he come from another planet?
The guitar riffs, enchanting, make you want to leave the Earth.
In any case, Bowie is having fun playing the chameleon with these titles: informant in turn, man on board a rocket, martian potential...
He hides and reveals at the same time, playing to adopt different personalities, as he has done throughout his career, notably with his characters Ziggy Stardust and Aladdin Sane.
No wonder he has a mask in his hand in the Louis Vuitton Invitation to Travel campaign, which he embodies in his new face.
It will appear in one of their commercials, broadcast from November 10.
Defence Minister Rob Nicholson insisted that wounded soldiers were not summarily released from the Canadian Armed Forces, and stressed that a transition process was followed by all soldiers before they returned to civilian life.
Attacked by the Liberals and New Democrats in the House of Commons, Nicholson assured that prior to their release, members of the military followed a transition plan in collaboration with their superiors.
