Early puberty: Getting older earlier
Studies show that African American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than white girls.
Physical changes do not mean that puberty is imminent
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible.
Experts think obesity epidemic could be trigger of early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is not as pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in family and child health issues.
Should a mother worry if her daughter’s breasts and pubic hair begin to grow at age 7 or 8?
At this week’s American Academy of Pediatrics conference in Orlando, Florida, paedoendocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes are fairly common among young Americans and represent a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring parents — in general, it doesn’t indicate a rapid shift toward full puberty,” Kaplowitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as budding breasts, hair under the arms and in the pubic area, and body odors, appear earlier in girls.
But there has only been a slight advance in the age of first menstruation over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12 and a half, compared to 12 three-quarters in 1970.
“Once the breast has begun to develop, it takes at least two or three years for the first menstrual period to appear,” said Kaplowitz, also the author of “Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem.”
Time is the most accurate test to know how puberty will evolve.
There is debate about what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but it is considered “early” when breast development is accompanied by sudden growth before the age of 8 years.
In most cases, development slows down or stops – this is something a pediatrician can follow closely.
Faster evolution may warrant tests performed by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatments to delay the onset of the first period and prevent other consequences: premature aging of the bones that can slow growth and small size in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug and hormone treatment are based on the child's age, developmental rate, growth rate, and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious with medications but recognizes that “controlling puberty can alleviate some behavioral problems and the feeling for young girls to be different from others.”
The other big problem is understandable: Parents simply don’t want their very young daughters to have their periods.
“They fear the risk of pregnancy or even how they will handle hygiene issues,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls a woman whose daughter had her first period at age 10.
Even though there were signs and we talked about the rules, she wasn’t emotionally prepared.
She came home from school frightened and upset to be the first of her friends.
There are many theories made public about the causes of early puberty.
Yet there is no consistent theory that the hormones contained in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment or sexual messages conveyed by the media are responsible.
Boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz says the most credible hypothesis is that of the obesity epidemic.
He participated in a study of girls aged 6 to 9 years that links the percentage of fat mass to the onset of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other influential factors.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than white girls.
There are various explanations.
Globally, the mechanisms of early puberty appear to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another problem: Although boys have younger facial and pubic area hairs, the trend toward true early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other physicians attending the PAA conference emphasized the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common, even in infants and toddlers.
“We need to be cautious about how we identify the true onset of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a child endocrinologist working at Goryeb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to ask their pediatrician for advice on how to talk to their child.
“This may mean having a conversation earlier than expected,” Kaplowitz said.
If you stay calm, your child will react well in general.
Girls whose puberty is early should be reassured that, even when it happens earlier than expected, the process is part of life.
