How Biometrics Will Invade Our Lives
Finished the passwords to enter to access your smartphone or pay for your purchases?
American, French or Japanese researchers predict a future where we will be recognized by the biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, deputy general manager of Morpho, even believes that "the century will be biometric".
Only biometrics will make it possible to ascertain the identity of a person performing transactions in a universe as transverse and transnational as the Internet.
Privacy organizations confirm this craze for biometrics, but are concerned.
In 2011 alone and in France, the Commission nationale de l'informatique et des libertés authorized 774 systems for recognizing fingerprints, the shape of the hand or the venous network of the hand in companies, administrations, canteens...
“Everyone will soon be able to be identified, anywhere and anytime,” said Justin Brookman, head of consumer privacy at the Center for Democracy and Technology in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, in some, and pessimism, in others?
Biometrics will be based on new techniques, which will make it possible to provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most used biometric data are fingerprints, the outline of the hand and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its constraints.
"For example, some people who work the concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are illegible," says Philippe Robin, technical director of the identity field at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand presuppose a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
It is both a security - we cannot capture these data without their knowledge - and a disadvantage: the procedure sometimes has to be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been carried out over the last twenty years on other approaches, such as facial recognition or iris (the colored part of the eye).
Thanks to the increased accuracy of the sensors and the computing capacity of the computers required for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
Accuracy of facial recognition has increased tenfold over the past five years, says Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture’s R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the UK and the Netherlands have deployed automatic border posts using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
“Today, we’re researching voice recognition or how to walk using sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment,” said Sridhar Iyengar, director of security research at Intel Labs.
A unique and unfalsifiable marker, DNA also arouses hope and concern.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered as the ultimate biometric data," confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Foresight at the CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime and in one hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognizing one person among others) and authentication (ensuring that the person is who he or she claims to be).
The identification so far concerned the issuance of identity papers: it is necessary to compare the biometric elements (fingerprints, photo, iris) with the information that the State has on all citizens already registered.
This helps to ensure that a person does not try to impersonate someone else.
This comparison principle may have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance to a hotel or store.
“We retrieve the images from the surveillance cameras and compare them to the photos of celebrities who circulate freely on the Internet,” explains Dany Nassif, in charge, at NEC France, of commercial development for biometric identification solutions.
Another use: taking a picture of a quidam standing in line in a store, tracking his progress through facial recognition and calculating the waiting time.
Authentication initially concerned physical access (borders, protected premises, canteens...) or logical access (opening a computer).
More recently, presence control has been added.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the friend pointing for another," justifies Cyrille Bataller, of Accenture.
But, increasingly, authentication will also concern transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from certain vendors by introducing your card and placing your hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the keystroke of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by the company Natural Security in partnership with banks and retailers: when paying in-store with his credit card, the customer does not type his code, but inserts his finger into a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is planned to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French traders.
Tips to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics appealing to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
"If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays in the box thirty seconds less, it is appreciable," explains the director of a large surface.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you tailor-made options.
And, finally, reassuring by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
“Fingerprints are stored on a first server; people’s identities are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure enclosure, which crashes if you try to move it,” lists Philippe Robin of Thales.
But, for lack of in-depth studies, it is impossible to know whether these discourses really convince users.
However, privacy specialists continue to be concerned.
“The advances in facial recognition, the proliferation of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, make me fear the worst: widespread surveillance,” said Andrew Patrick of the Office of the Privacy Commissioner of Canada.
