Scientists have just shed light on how a dog’s tail movements are related to his mood.
Previous studies had found that happy dogs moved their tail more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while nervous dogs moved their tail more to the left.
But now scientists say dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: “Everyone knows that in humans, the left and right sides of the brain are involved differently in stimuli that arouse positive or negative emotions.”
Here we tried to see what was going on with other species.
He added that just as in humans, in dogs the right side of the brain is responsible for movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres play a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to other dogs’ disordered tail movements, the researchers followed animals watching movies featuring other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
It probably won’t be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side and sometimes to the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: “We presented dogs with films featuring other dogs – either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other confounding factor – and we were able to manipulate the movement of the tail and present it as going further left or right.”
When the animals saw an expressionless dog stirring its tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog stirring its tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail deviating mainly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog wagging the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
Rather, he believes that dogs know from experience the movements they should or should not worry about.
He added: “If you meet other dogs repeatedly and you notice that, most of the time, moving their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react based on that experience.”
The researchers say the findings could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand their animals’ emotions.
Canine behavior expert John Bradshaw, a visiting professor at the School of Veterinary Sciences at the University of Bristol, said this is not the first study to look at the importance of left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University discovered that dogs turned their heads left when they looked at an aggressive dog and right when it was a cheerful dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: “Dogs went more easily to a robot dog when its tail moved to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious – the opposite of what appears in the Italian study.”
He said the differences could come from the fact that the dogs that participated in the different studies did not fully consider movie animals or robot dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs react to real dogs could be helpful, he explained.
“Although many evidence, found in different mammals, indicates that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified – and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviors can be recorded, it will probably not be long before we understand why their tail sometimes moves on one side and sometimes on the other.
