The cry of despair of an Obama voter
I voted twice for President Obama, believing in the possibility of change
He says Obama made laudable efforts thwarted by Republican Party obstructionism
The obstructionism does not excuse the difficulties of the Obamacare site, nor the drone attacks
Obama's 2008 campaign memoir is a sad reminder of what might have happened
Nathaniel P. Morris is a 2nd year medical student at Harvard Medical School.
I’m reading a very sad book these days.
It is a book that I thought would encourage me during the late second year of medicine and give me hope.
It’s called “The Audacity to Win” and it’s the memoirs of Barack Obama’s 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finished the medical records of my patients in the evening and I went to bed, this book takes me back to the time when politics inspired millions of people and speeches could take your breath away.
The election ended with an overwhelming victory and news anchors took the time to reflect on the historical nature of the moment.
My comrades cried for joy and my parents kept all the newspapers they found.
A young team of visionaries was advancing toward the White House and the nation was ready for change.
During Obama's transition period before taking office in 2008, he had 82% favorable opinions.
And then I close the book.
Returning to the present is a difficult awakening, it’s like coming out of a dream.
It is difficult to remember these days full of optimism, they are like distant memories, a sad reminder of the opportunities of the past.
The change really happened in the years that followed the first time I voted.
It had nothing to do with what I had imagined.
I credit Obama with great achievements, from the passage of the Affordable Care Act to the departure of Iraq from our military, to the end of “not seen nor known” and the assassination of Osama bin Laden.
Moreover, I believe that partisan obstructionism has destroyed too many efforts to move our nation forward in immigration reforms, public health care and the closure of Guantanamo, among other things.
But after repeatedly defending the Obama administration in front of my peers and colleagues, I can no longer provide explanations.
I am on the verge of political despair.
Republican obstruction cannot explain the wiretapping of foreign leaders, nor the attacks on innocent foreign children by drones.
It cannot explain that the National Security Agency collects data on the privacy of Americans, nor the impeachment of whistleblowers who reveal the misdeeds of the government.
It cannot justify the assassination of Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, without trial, nor the evasion of public funding and the exceedance of authorized spending during presidential campaigns.
It cannot justify the findings of a report that says the White House’s efforts to silence the media are the “most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration.”
And, more recently, it cannot excuse the impossibility of designing a simple website for more than three years after the Affordable Care Act was ratified.
I don't know if that's what I was expecting.
If, at the age of 18, I was supposed to understand that governance could contradict the political campaigns that preceded it.
Obviously, the election function is not predictable, because the opposition political party and events that happen by chance, such as the Newton massacre, influence our public conversation.
However, all the examples I have listed above seem to be largely the choice of the administration.
That's what bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney presented a confusing and unrefined alternative that did not seem to determine his policies or positions.
I felt that Obama, elected for a second term and freed from the pressure of future elections, would keep the promises that have been heard for so long.
Yet, while the favorable opinion index has plunged below 45% this week, it’s even harder to get back to 2008 through this book.
It makes me crave the many promises that have fled.
This week, I read the part of the book that describes how Obama suffered huge losses to Clinton at the Pennsylvania Primaries.
At a post-campaign meeting, he told his team that they needed to get back on track and stay true to their cause.
“I want us to refocus on our talent,” he said.
We need to remember who we are.
Five years later, Mr. President, and I no longer agree with you.
The views expressed in this commentary are only those of Nathaniel Morris.
