Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presents at Danse Danse her two new group choreographies: the first inspired by the inks and poems of Henri Michaux, the second inspired by the famous piano solos Gymnopédies de Satie.
An evening that allows you to see the whole prism of Chouinard, from art to tics and from black to white.
A white screen serves as a background wall.
On the carpet, as white, in the immense space that is the Théâtre Maisonneuve, advances, in profile, thin as a line and dressed in black, a body.
On the screen, an ink of Henri Michaux is projected.
The body, a simple trait, takes its shape.
And this shape will be that of the whole room: a string of physical imitations of the drawings.
The dancers, entirely dressed in black, only hands and face uncovered, wait on either side of the playground, rush when the next letter appears, embody it, come out running.
This black and white game by Henri Michaux is made in relay of solos, in group in unison (a mass that makes solo), in large group of twelve solos where each performs his sign.
We think of "Glory of the Morning", where, in solo, Chouinard performed a series of choreographic tasks written on cartels, posed online in the forescene.
It's the same principle, giant PowerPoint version.
Here, the music is loud, percussions and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the pace always fast.
There will be a break when Carol Prieur takes refuge under the dance mat, to deliver, microphone in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a part of Michaux’s poem, monochord and monotonous in the cry, and will continue dancing.
And the music to start again, and the sequence to resume.
This sound and energetic discharge, long, if possible, ends up deafening and numbing.
As does the regularity of the visual rhythm.
There are some beautiful flashes - the creation of images has always been a force at Chouinard - like those hairs that crumble or those black fabrics that lengthen the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
We have the impression that the choreographer, instead of going to meet the work of Michaux, has imposed itself, with its tics.
As a result, the bodies appear flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux’s inks, like Gestalt forms, open up a broader and more porous imagination than dance.
Only the end, in negative, with its dancers chopped by a strobe light and white signs in a suddenly black theater, touches the magic.
The public liked it, the welcome was warm.
The Gymnopedias, after the intermission, is richer.
The scene is partly draped in grey, the dancers and a piano are covered with fabrics, like furniture in a neglected house.
At the piano, dancers take turns to play the scores.
Their clumsiness in music, touching, give a real fragility.
On stage, couples pass, in romantic duets, very sensual, even erotic.
Group work, small solos of transitions, ensembles that move, choirs, writing is less binary.
Clowns appear, also familiar to Chouinard, with a red nose, in very polarized male-female love parades.
Loves are carnivores, fugitives or gamers.
The gestures, the laughter and the small cries beautifully transpose the archaic, the grace and the ridicule of the bodies in coitus, of the beings that merge.
But the play takes its real flight after salvation.
A clown returns to the stage when the audience leaves.
There, everything becomes permissible: the fourth wall falls, the universes explored overlap, the dancers cabotine, descend among the spectators, gloat, smoke, short-circuit, play codes of applause, stretch the sauce in a cleverly calculated disorder that remains sensual.
Joy and madness permeate, and it is Chouinard's art, there, to contaminate the public.
