John Kerry has admitted, an unprecedented fact, that American espionage “has gone too far in an inappropriate way.”
John Kerry indicated a softening of the defensive attitude of the United States towards its surveillance programs by admitting, an unprecedented fact, that on several occasions, the espionage “had gone too far inappropriately”.
The Secretary of State also admitted that he had, like Barack Obama, ruled on “autopilot” when a series of incendiary revelations by whistleblower Edward Snowden about the NSA’s espionage activities surfaced.
The leaks have put the U.S. government at the center of a diplomatic storm with its allies.
Speaking at an intergovernmental conference in London via video link, Mr. Kerry said: "It is undeniable that the President, myself and other members of the government became aware of certain things in autopilot mode because we had the possibility, from the Second World War to the difficult years of the Cold War, then of course September 11th."
He then became the first high-ranking member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. espionage had crossed the line, but insisted that everyone’s rights had not been violated.
He said: “In some cases, it went too far inappropriately.”
And the President is committed to trying to clarify and make it clear to people that he is now conducting a thorough review of these practices so that no one feels deceived.
I assure you that innocent people will not be abused in this process.
Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA was a force acting for good and that its surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added: “We live in a new world where people are ready to get blown up.”
There is a radical extremism in the world that is determined to try to kill people, blow them up and attack governments.
What if you could intercept their communications and stop them before they act?
We have indeed prevented planes from falling, buildings from exploding and people from being murdered because we were able to learn the facts in advance.
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will travel to Europe to address concerns about the alleged U.S. espionage case and convince Europeans of the need to continue joint counter-terrorism efforts with the United States, the chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said on Thursday.
Sen. Chris Murphy of Connecticut said he had spoken to members of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about threats they had made regarding a possible withdrawal of counter-terrorism organizations due to the sense of frustration oversight by the National Security Agency.
“It is really important for the protection of national security in the United States that Europeans remain with us in our mutual commitment to the fight against terrorism,” Murphy, a Democrat serving his first term, and chairman of the U.S. Senate’s European Affairs Subcommittee, said in an interview from Washington.
And I will go to Europe to make them understand that we must continue to work together to fight terrorism, despite the anger provoked by the NSA’s programs.
The press reports that the NSA has captured millions of communications in Europe, which has undermined relations with some US allies, however the agency’s director said this week that it was inaccurate and a misunderstanding as it concerned metadata that NATO allies had collected and shared with the US.
Other revelations included documents leaked by Snowden that the NSA had intercepted data and communications from German Chancellor Angela Merkel’s mobile phone and those of 34 other heads of state.
The director of intelligence services, James Clapper, justified spying on the allies by stating that it was necessary and that it was a common practice on both sides.
In this atmosphere of turmoil, Murphy said his office was organizing a congressional trip, which is expected to take place this year, and he hoped the delegation would include members from both parties and both houses.
The names of other participating legislators are expected to be released in the coming days.
He said the route had yet to be determined.
Murphy said the purpose of this trip was to improve relationships, but also to show “affective firmness.”
He explained that European heads of state should be honest with their citizens about the type of espionage programs they have been running themselves for years.
“We can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, but they also need to understand that we are not the only ones in the world to spy,” Murphy said.
In the meantime, Kerry has planned to travel to the Middle East and Poland this weekend to deal with the resentment generated by US strategies in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as US surveillance activities.
